Adamawa state government has been tasked to pay PTA levy in public schools and activate SDGs goals, to reduce 886,634 out of school children in the state. Mr Monday Osasah, Executive Director, African Centre for Leadership, Strategy and Development, made the recommendation Friday in Yola for robust free education declared in the state. Osasah, lauded the recruitment of 2000 teachers and urged government to ensure their posting after recruitment should not be skewed against the rural areas to ensure fairness and quality across the board. He stated a survey conducted by the centre indicate that, Maiha has the highest number of out of schoolgirls, with 66.7, followed by Song 63.3 and Numan, 45 per cent. Osasah noted that, the statistic implies that, on the average, over 50 per cent of the girls of school age are not in school. The centre had established seven peer leaning clubs with 254 girls who are though basic English and Mathematics in the three pilot councils in the state. Government should activate all the SDGs goals in the state to ensure no child is denied right to education especially girl child. Proper monitoring mechanism for robust implementation of free education in Adamawa state. 